WEBVTT

00:04.080 --> 00:05.490
[Ryn]
Previously on Siren.

00:05.500 --> 00:06.910
It's Mom.

00:06.920 --> 00:08.114
She in the emergency room.

00:08.120 --> 00:11.908
[moaning]

00:11.920 --> 00:14.036
Ryn help Ben's mother.

00:14.040 --> 00:18.158
Stem cells_ from
a deepwater marlne creature.

00:18.170 --> 00:22.038
[laughs] Imagine what
your father's going to say.

00:22.040 --> 00:23.951
[Helen]
That's my mother.

00:23.960 --> 00:26.997
Yes. A long time ago,
she was part of the group.

00:27.000 --> 00:29.912
What happened
to your folks wasn't right.

00:29.920 --> 00:31.660
I'll never forget it.

00:31.670 --> 00:33.877
[Xander] Was sleeping
with me part of the job?

00:33.880 --> 00:35.871
I'm here
because I care about you.

00:35.880 --> 00:37.495
Oh. Then you look me
in the eye

00:37.500 --> 00:39.991
and you tell me
that you're here
just to check on me.

00:40.000 --> 00:41.911
You're not just
a little bit curious
about where they went?

00:43.880 --> 00:45.199
[banging]

00:45.210 --> 00:46.199
-[Ben] Ryn!
-Raah!

00:46.210 --> 00:47.108
Ryn!

00:47.120 --> 00:49.111
Aaaah!

00:50.790 --> 00:51.916
[Ben] Ryn!

00:51.920 --> 00:53.114
[Maddie] Ryn!

00:58.710 --> 01:00.780
[panﬁng]

01:06.460 --> 01:07.609
Ryn!

01:11.080 --> 01:12.069
[Maddie] Ryn!

01:13.080 --> 01:14.286
Ryn!

01:18.250 --> 01:23.074
[ominous music playing]

01:34.420 --> 01:37.036
[high-pitched call]

01:39.620 --> 01:41.247
Ryn!

01:41.250 --> 01:43.206
Ryn, where are you?!

01:43.210 --> 01:44.245
Wait. Wait, wait, wait.

01:48.880 --> 01:51.075
[flapping]

01:51.080 --> 01:52.240
She could be anywhere.

01:52.250 --> 01:54.457
We can't stop, Maddie.

01:56.420 --> 01:58.115
How are we going
to find her?

01:59.210 --> 02:00.245
We need help.

02:00.250 --> 02:01.820
From who?

02:03.670 --> 02:05.160
Nicole.

02:05.170 --> 02:06.569
You really think
we can trust her?

02:06.580 --> 02:08.116
We don't have a choice,
Maddie.

02:09.540 --> 02:11.326
She's out here,
and she's dangerous,

02:11.330 --> 02:12.957
and we need
to find her now.

02:18.580 --> 02:21.208
You got
everything you wanted.

02:21.210 --> 02:23.997
Two of my best friends
eating out the palm
of your hands.

02:25.170 --> 02:28.287
Willing test subject for,
I don't know,

02:28.290 --> 02:30.372
whatever the hell
your people are doing.

02:30.380 --> 02:32.280
That's not everything
I wanted.

02:35.380 --> 02:37.371
Look, I don't expect you
to forgive me.

02:37.380 --> 02:39.029
I mean, how could you?

02:39.040 --> 02:40.530
You don't even know me.

02:40.540 --> 02:43.998
Look, I gotta get this place
ready for business, so...

02:48.380 --> 02:50.371
My older brother
was deployed two years ago.

02:51.830 --> 02:52.819
Iraq.

02:54.250 --> 02:55.740
I enlisted
right after him.

02:59.170 --> 03:00.535
Grew up in a military family,

03:00.540 --> 03:02.076
so it was
kind of the thing to do.

03:03.420 --> 03:05.285
Yeah, family business,
I get it.

03:07.460 --> 03:10.247
First week there,
his convoy was hit by an IED.

03:13.120 --> 03:14.326
He survived,

03:14.330 --> 03:15.536
but with lots of damage.

03:19.330 --> 03:20.376
Wow.

03:21.460 --> 03:23.200
I'm sorry.

03:23.210 --> 03:26.873
I didn't see any action,
but I had to do something.

03:26.880 --> 03:28.916
I heard about
this military program.

03:28.920 --> 03:31.662
Supposed to help
wounded soldiers walk again.

03:31.670 --> 03:35.379
They said it involved the use
of "exotic" stem cells.

03:35.380 --> 03:37.200
Yeah, that must
have been a weird day

03:37.210 --> 03:39.667
when you found out
what that meant.

03:39.670 --> 03:41.740
I volunteered to help
in any way that I could.

03:42.790 --> 03:43.950
I was low level at ﬁrst,

03:43.960 --> 03:45.450
until the program's leader--

03:45.460 --> 03:48.952
guy named Aldon Decker--
killed himself.

03:50.210 --> 03:51.199
Yeah, I met him.

03:53.040 --> 03:56.203
Military asked me
to go undercover
in Bristol Cove.

03:57.380 --> 04:00.452
IfI could help figure
out why Decker died,

04:00.460 --> 04:01.916
they'd be able
to continue his work.

04:03.750 --> 04:06.207
I never wanted to hurt anyone.

04:06.210 --> 04:08.576
[cell phone buzzing]

04:10.620 --> 04:12.281
Well, duty calls, I guess.

04:13.290 --> 04:15.246
[buzzing]

04:16.710 --> 04:18.029
[beeps]

04:18.040 --> 04:19.075
Hey.

04:20.920 --> 04:22.239
[Ben]
We did this to her.

04:22.250 --> 04:24.115
The stem cell extraction,

04:24.120 --> 04:26.497
it caused Ryn to have
some kind of reaction.

04:26.500 --> 04:28.286
Her cortisol levels spiked.

04:28.290 --> 04:30.246
Maybe some kind
of defensive response.

04:30.250 --> 04:31.786
Back someone in a corner,
they're gonna react.

04:31.790 --> 04:33.075
You should've
told me sooner.

04:33.080 --> 04:34.616
We thought
we had it under control.

04:34.620 --> 04:36.531
Clearly, you didn't.

04:36.540 --> 04:38.076
I have to alert my CD.

04:38.080 --> 04:39.536
You should think about that.

04:39.540 --> 04:40.825
What's to think about?

04:40.830 --> 04:42.741
She's dangerous
and on the loose.

04:42.750 --> 04:44.035
She ran into the woods.

04:44.040 --> 04:46.201
We can all find her
and bring her back.

04:46.210 --> 04:48.280
And do it without all of us,
including you,

04:48.290 --> 04:49.700
having to get burned.

04:50.750 --> 04:52.115
How do you think
your superiors

04:52.120 --> 04:54.452
are gonna react to you
letting this get out of hand?

04:54.460 --> 04:57.452
My only mistake was putting
Ryn back in your care.

04:57.460 --> 04:58.700
It doesn't matter
whose fault it is.

04:58.710 --> 05:00.200
We need to find Ryn.

05:00.210 --> 05:01.666
It's why we called you.

05:05.750 --> 05:06.819
Got the satellite link,

05:06.830 --> 05:08.741
just have to set
the target area.

05:08.750 --> 05:11.492
You're not gonna, like,
nuke Bri_stol Cove
from orbit are you?

05:11.500 --> 05:13.161
It's thermal imaging.

05:13.170 --> 05:16.242
Should help us pinpoint
exactly where Ryn is.

05:16.250 --> 05:18.741
Yeah, but how do you know
it's her and not
some rando campers?

05:18.750 --> 05:20.615
Ryn's core body temp
is different than ours.

05:20.620 --> 05:21.826
Ninety-two degrees.

05:24.830 --> 05:27.879
[beeping]

05:27.880 --> 05:29.575
If that's her,
she's moving fast.

05:34.000 --> 05:35.570
[panﬁng]

05:35.580 --> 05:37.821
Ryn!

05:37.830 --> 05:39.206
[Maddie]
Where are you?!

05:39.210 --> 05:41.826
Well, so much
for a quiet morning.

05:41.830 --> 05:43.161
[hisses]

05:43.170 --> 05:45.741
-[sniffing]
-[twig snaps]

05:45.750 --> 05:47.536
-[animal grunts]
-[hisses]

05:51.830 --> 05:53.115
[soft hiss]

05:53.120 --> 05:54.109
[gunshot]

06:03.500 --> 06:04.910
Dad, it's a person.

06:06.500 --> 06:07.785
Rifle down, now.

06:09.790 --> 06:11.030
Are you okay?!

06:11.040 --> 06:13.497
You could get yourself
killed out here!

06:15.960 --> 06:17.916
Hey, hey, hey, hey!
Easy, easy.

06:17.920 --> 06:20.036
Careful, buddy.
There's a girl out here.

06:20.040 --> 06:21.496
I don't know
what she's on,

06:21.500 --> 06:22.569
but she's gonna
get herself hurt.

06:22.580 --> 06:23.877
Did you see
where she went?

06:25.330 --> 06:27.912
If you're smart,
you'll get out of here.

06:27.920 --> 06:30.707
[intense music playing]

06:37.920 --> 06:39.956
What the hell, man!

06:39.960 --> 06:40.995
Where is she?!

06:41.000 --> 06:42.206
She didn't come this way.

06:43.710 --> 06:44.825
Maddie.

06:45.880 --> 06:47.416
-Come on.
-Come on.

07:01.790 --> 07:03.326
[hisses]

07:03.330 --> 07:04.456
Ryn.

07:04.460 --> 07:05.996
[hisses]

07:06.000 --> 07:06.819
Ryn, it's Maddie.

07:09.040 --> 07:10.996
Do you understand
what's happening?

07:11.000 --> 07:11.785
[hisses]

07:11.790 --> 07:12.779
Ryn!

07:15.790 --> 07:16.779
Ryn, please.

07:19.920 --> 07:21.319
Please.

07:24.120 --> 07:29.035
[singing ethereal Siren song]

07:41.120 --> 07:44.032
[song intensifies]

07:44.040 --> 07:46.201
No, no, no, no, no!

07:46.210 --> 07:47.666
Maddie, Maddie, Maddie!
No,no,no!

07:47.670 --> 07:48.876
[song stops abruptly]

07:48.880 --> 07:50.825
No, no, no, no!

07:50.830 --> 07:52.912
Look at me.
You okay?

07:58.920 --> 07:59.955
Ryn?

08:01.290 --> 08:02.871
Can you hear me?

08:02.880 --> 08:04.199
Ben?

08:06.040 --> 08:07.246
What did I do?

08:20.040 --> 08:22.201
[sweeping]

08:29.750 --> 08:31.115
[Ben] You're sure
you're all right?

08:31.120 --> 08:36.069
I mean, no accelerated
heart rate? Anxiety?

08:36.080 --> 08:38.992
I mean, a little shalq,
but other than that,
I feel fine.

08:41.250 --> 08:43.491
You don't remember
anything, Ryn?

08:43.500 --> 08:46.913
I remember,
but could not stop.

08:46.920 --> 08:49.070
It's okay.
It's not your fault.

08:49.080 --> 08:52.413
Not okay.
This is not Ryn.

08:53.790 --> 08:55.030
Something change me.

08:56.380 --> 09:00.077
Know I do bad thing,
but do it anyway.

09:00.080 --> 09:02.036
How do you feel now?

09:02.040 --> 09:03.200
Okay, now.

09:03.210 --> 09:05.531
When I sing,
I feel better.

09:05.540 --> 09:09.374
Ryn told us before
that the song does
something for her, too.

09:09.380 --> 09:10.870
Whatever it releases,

09:10.880 --> 09:12.700
_ it seems like
It's strong enough

09:12.710 --> 09:15.952
to reduce the built-up
adrenaline at a rapid rate.

09:15.960 --> 09:19.532
Might be a good idea
to keep the needles
away from her for a while.

09:19.540 --> 09:20.780
[Ben] Yeah, right.

09:20.790 --> 09:22.917
But what about you, Maddie?

09:24.120 --> 09:25.997
What do you mean?

09:26.000 --> 09:27.160
I don't know.
How about the fact

09:27.170 --> 09:28.706
that Ryn just did
her thing to you?

09:28.710 --> 09:30.109
You're acting
like it's nothing.

09:30.120 --> 09:31.997
Hey, we're working
through it, Xan.

09:32.000 --> 09:33.740
Says the guy who's had
this song stuck in his head

09:33.750 --> 09:35.160
for, what,
the last couple months?

09:36.330 --> 09:38.958
Look, can we just--

09:38.960 --> 09:42.282
just fact check, yeah,
for, like, a second?

09:42.290 --> 09:45.953
So the three of you are
working with the military

09:45.960 --> 09:48.576
to get some genetic goo
out of Ryn

09:48.580 --> 09:50.161
and inject it
into Ben's mom,

09:50.170 --> 09:54.709
and because of all this,
Ryn just went "beast mode."

09:56.040 --> 09:57.780
[laughs]
I mean, I'm sorry,

09:57.790 --> 09:59.166
but y'all need to get
your damn heads checked!

10:03.290 --> 10:05.030
That's just
one guy's opinion, so...

10:08.040 --> 10:09.029
He's not wrong.

10:10.330 --> 10:12.070
About checking our heads.

10:14.080 --> 10:15.991
Maybe it's time
we considered it.

10:18.170 --> 10:20.741
Decker's brain scans,
the ones you showed me.

10:21.880 --> 10:23.745
Can we do the same for us?

10:23.750 --> 10:25.570
Yeah. Just gotta get you
back to the lab.

10:25.580 --> 10:27.741
If we know exactly
how the song's
affecting us--

10:27.750 --> 10:29.320
Maybe we can do
something about it.

10:42.750 --> 10:44.741
You should've
discussed it with me.

10:44.750 --> 10:47.241
Instead you go injecting
yourself with another
experimental treatment.

10:47.250 --> 10:48.786
I mean, I know you
want to get better, but--

10:48.790 --> 10:51.076
I think
it did make me better.

10:51.080 --> 10:52.069
Those awful side effects

10:52.080 --> 10:54.036
from the previous treatment
are gone.

10:54.040 --> 10:56.201
Even the nerve pain
that I used to have
is a little better.

10:56.210 --> 10:59.418
I'm not going to be running
marathons anytime soon,
but it's a start.

10:59.420 --> 11:00.660
You should've at least
stayed In the hospital

11:00.670 --> 11:02.240
so they could monitor you.

11:02.250 --> 11:05.117
You know the chances
of infection are higher there.

11:05.120 --> 11:07.953
They said that I could
recuperate at home.

11:07.960 --> 11:11.111
Ijust... It got
really, really close there

11:11.120 --> 11:12.872
in the hospital
for a few minutes.

11:14.120 --> 11:16.918
Ithought
was gonna lose you.

11:16.920 --> 11:18.740
But things
are finally turning around.

11:20.170 --> 11:21.535
And we have our son
to thank for that.

11:21.540 --> 11:23.201
What do you mean?

11:23.210 --> 11:25.075
Ben is the one who found
the new treatment.

11:25.080 --> 11:28.709
He even had a specialized
military doctor
to administer it.

11:28.710 --> 11:30.280
These guys are
the best of the best.

11:30.290 --> 11:32.281
So you've both been
keeping this from me.

11:32.290 --> 11:34.326
Don't blame him.

11:34.330 --> 11:36.821
His intention was to help me,
not to deceive you.

11:36.830 --> 11:38.377
With everything
that's been going on.

11:41.170 --> 11:44.207
Now is the perfect time
to put it to rest.

11:44.210 --> 11:45.700
[dialing]

11:47.420 --> 11:49.115
-[line ringing]
-[frustrated sigh]

11:49.120 --> 11:53.705
Are you sure you're up
for entertaining right now, Mom?

11:53.710 --> 11:55.996
Every day feels better
than the last.

11:56.000 --> 11:57.319
I'll see what we can do,

11:57.330 --> 11:58.911
but the timing right now is--

11:58.920 --> 12:00.569
[Elaine]
Everything, Ben.

12:00.580 --> 12:02.536
If I've learned anything,

12:02.540 --> 12:05.703
it's that time is not something
I can take for granted anymore.

12:05.710 --> 12:08.076
All of us could use
a fresh start.

12:08.080 --> 12:09.160
That's easier said
than done.

12:09.170 --> 12:10.205
Nonsense.

12:10.210 --> 12:12.280
Tomorrow night, 7 PM.

12:12.290 --> 12:13.700
Nothing fancy.

12:13.710 --> 12:16.247
You can come
with Maddie, and

12:16.250 --> 12:18.491
I want you to bring
that girl from the hospital,

12:18.500 --> 12:21.162
the one who helped me.
I need to thank her.

12:21.170 --> 12:22.614
Mom, uh...

12:22.620 --> 12:25.168
Ben. Please.

12:28.210 --> 12:29.279
Okay.

12:31.830 --> 12:33.115
[beeps]

12:35.120 --> 12:37.668
[MRI machine humming]

12:43.250 --> 12:44.285
[humming stops]

12:46.420 --> 12:49.321
[table clicks and whirs]

12:53.500 --> 12:54.990
You okay?

12:55.000 --> 12:56.376
Yeah, fine.

12:56.380 --> 12:58.075
How's your mom?

12:58.080 --> 13:02.369
Uh, she wants us to go
to dinner tomorrow night.

13:02.380 --> 13:04.200
She wants me
to bring Ryn, too.

13:05.670 --> 13:07.376
Ben's mother is better?

13:07.380 --> 13:09.666
Must be, if she's feeling
good enough to see people.

13:09.670 --> 13:12.377
Look, Ryn and I have to go,

13:12.380 --> 13:13.369
but if you don't
feel up to it--

13:13.380 --> 13:14.369
It's fine.

13:14.380 --> 13:15.870
You sure?

13:15.880 --> 13:18.246
Wouldn't want to upset her,

13:18.250 --> 13:19.239
not in her condition, right?

13:19.250 --> 13:20.877
Yeah.

13:20.880 --> 13:23.075
How soon until
we see the results?

13:23.080 --> 13:24.206
Doctor says
tomorrow morning.

13:26.620 --> 13:28.247
[Nicole] Your turn.

13:28.250 --> 13:30.036
Have to look
at Ben's brain now.

13:31.290 --> 13:33.201
[clicks, whirring]

13:41.080 --> 13:43.207
[MRI machine humming]

13:46.000 --> 13:47.991
[movie projector clicking]

14:01.880 --> 14:03.279
[knock on door]

14:07.580 --> 14:08.877
Helen?

14:08.880 --> 14:10.450
Oh.

14:10.460 --> 14:12.746
-[He|en] Hi. [laughs]
-[Maddie] Is everything
all right?

14:12.750 --> 14:14.536
Your message said you needed
to talk to us right away.

14:14.540 --> 14:17.168
Yes. Thank you
for coming over so quickly.

14:21.790 --> 14:24.202
Like TV, but not.

14:26.290 --> 14:27.530
Uh, this is called film.

14:29.210 --> 14:31.610
Those are my parents.

14:31.620 --> 14:34.532
These are the only images
I have of them together.

14:34.540 --> 14:37.748
That bun in the oven,
that's me.

14:37.750 --> 14:41.288
My father died a few weeks
before I was born.

14:41.290 --> 14:43.497
How did Helen's father die?

14:43.500 --> 14:45.991
Brain aneurysm.

14:46.000 --> 14:47.911
At least that's what
I was lead to believe.

14:47.920 --> 14:49.569
What do you mean?

14:49.580 --> 14:51.571
That's why I asked you
to come over.

14:51.580 --> 14:53.116
We have a lot
to catch up on.

14:53.120 --> 14:55.748
We couldn't agree more.

14:55.750 --> 14:57.661
There are more people
like Helen?

14:57.670 --> 14:58.989
More family?

14:59.000 --> 15:01.161
Much more, but...

15:01.170 --> 15:02.410
You think
they're dangerous?

15:02.420 --> 15:04.741
[Helen]
I can't be sure.

15:07.670 --> 15:10.912
I just wish I knew
what wasn't right about it.

15:10.920 --> 15:12.911
What do you think they want?

15:12.920 --> 15:15.821
As far as I can tell,
to know that
their secret is safe.

15:15.830 --> 15:18.742
To protect themselves
from the outside world.

15:18.750 --> 15:21.537
Secrecy hasn't been
a problem for us.

15:21.540 --> 15:24.202
Assuming you can trust
your military friends.

15:24.210 --> 15:26.110
If it wasn't
for their help,

15:26.120 --> 15:28.702
Ryn might not be
sitting here right now.

15:28.710 --> 15:30.325
I'm better now.

15:30.330 --> 15:33.242
And just in time
for dinner tomorrow night.

15:33.250 --> 15:34.820
She invited you, too?

15:40.080 --> 15:41.240
Thanks for the tea.

15:41.250 --> 15:42.285
Mm, all right.

15:43.380 --> 15:44.495
[Ben]
Good night, Helen.

15:51.330 --> 15:54.379
[somber music playing]

16:27.710 --> 16:29.826
I can't believe it's real.

16:29.830 --> 16:32.993
All those myths
about the song.

16:33.000 --> 16:36.163
That it could do something
like this to the human brain.

16:36.170 --> 16:37.569
Amazing.

16:37.580 --> 16:38.956
Which one's which?

16:40.380 --> 16:42.496
Decker's, yours,
and mine.

16:44.500 --> 16:45.819
Decker's very dark.

16:45.830 --> 16:48.162
Yes. Lesions of some sort.

16:50.380 --> 16:52.450
Maddie's not so dark.

16:52.460 --> 16:53.779
[Maddie]
Because it just happened,

16:53.790 --> 16:55.166
and you just sang to me.

16:56.170 --> 16:57.569
But there is
something there.

16:58.880 --> 17:01.075
The damage to yours
seems to be somewhere

17:01.080 --> 17:04.959
between hers
and Aldon Decker's.

17:04.960 --> 17:06.746
Let's hope
it stays that way.

17:06.750 --> 17:08.786
I do this to Ben and Maddie?

17:08.790 --> 17:10.746
Make heads dark?

17:10.750 --> 17:13.321
No. Well,
not intentionally.

17:13.330 --> 17:15.878
The question is,
why is it doing that?

17:17.210 --> 17:18.746
When Ben has struggled
with it,

17:18.750 --> 17:20.786
he seems _
to become more obsessrve.

17:20.790 --> 17:23.327
It seems to tap
into the prefrontal cortex,

17:23.330 --> 17:26.379
which controls_ reason
and emotion.

17:26.380 --> 17:29.577
Another way of saying
"impulse control."

17:29.580 --> 17:32.287
That means how we choose
to act, good or bad.

17:33.920 --> 17:36.878
Song makes you do things
you don't want to.

17:36.880 --> 17:38.279
Like Ryn.

17:38.290 --> 17:41.327
Not exactly.

17:41.330 --> 17:45.414
I think in our case,
it might make us
do things we want to do,

17:45.420 --> 17:47.911
but usually stop
ourselves from doing.

17:47.920 --> 17:49.615
[Maddie] Just because it
makes you more obsessive

17:49.620 --> 17:51.326
doesn't mean
it'll do the same to me.

17:51.330 --> 17:52.991
If it does
anything at all.

17:53.000 --> 17:54.376
[Ben]
Right. Like alcohol.

17:54.380 --> 17:56.245
Drinking affects
everyone differently.

17:56.250 --> 17:58.616
If we could record
the song itself,

17:58.620 --> 17:59.826
we could look
into its effects.

17:59.830 --> 18:01.661
I do this before.

18:01.670 --> 18:03.956
Sing for recording.
For Ben and Maddie.

18:03.960 --> 18:06.030
We've been _
wanting to analyze It,

18:06.040 --> 18:07.029
but not had the means.

18:07.040 --> 18:08.826
Maybe it's the only way.

18:08.830 --> 18:11.617
See if it's a bell
that can be un-rung.

18:11.620 --> 18:14.919
[cell phone ringing]

18:17.460 --> 18:19.701
Hey, Mom?
It's not a really good time.

18:21.080 --> 18:22.115
Dad can't help?

18:24.830 --> 18:26.912
All right.
I'll be right over.

18:28.750 --> 18:30.536
I gotta get
over to my mom's.

18:30.540 --> 18:32.246
She needs help,
doesn't want
to bother my dad.

18:32.250 --> 18:33.990
I'll come with you.

18:34.000 --> 18:35.285
No, you keep working.

18:35.290 --> 18:36.325
I'll see you tonight.

18:37.540 --> 18:38.529
Maddie?

18:39.710 --> 18:41.871
Call me if anything...

18:41.880 --> 18:43.575
You'll be
the first to know.

18:55.380 --> 18:58.452
[pop music playing]

18:58.460 --> 19:02.453
[music grows distorted]

19:02.460 --> 19:05.998
[Siren song echoing]

19:08.460 --> 19:11.611
[rock music playing]

19:13.210 --> 19:16.202
[male singer]
Tell me where to hide

19:19.790 --> 19:21.781
[Ben sighs]

19:21.790 --> 19:22.825
[keyboard clicks]

19:26.920 --> 19:27.909
Incredible.

19:29.120 --> 19:30.496
This is my song?

19:30.500 --> 19:32.377
Yeah.
Broken down into pieces.

19:32.380 --> 19:34.701
[fragment of Siren song plays]

19:34.710 --> 19:36.029
Song is broken?

19:36.040 --> 19:38.577
No, no, no.
The-- The pieces are,

19:38.580 --> 19:39.956
mixed together
to make one sound.

19:39.960 --> 19:40.949
One song.

19:40.960 --> 19:41.995
[lower fragment playing]

19:42.000 --> 19:43.706
[higher fragment playing]

19:43.710 --> 19:46.372
One song composed of hundreds
of frequencies and layers.

19:48.040 --> 19:50.281
This many layered frequencies
from one voice.

19:50.290 --> 19:52.110
How is that possible?

19:52.120 --> 19:55.419
All different levels,
polyphonics, amplitudes.

19:55.420 --> 19:56.990
I've never_ seen
anything like It,

19:57.000 --> 19:59.036
not even from whales
or dolphins.

19:59.040 --> 20:01.031
